        {
            "id": 1,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "Apoptosis",
            "relation": "BACKGROUND"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "induced through the TCR in CD4+ T cells",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT"
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "is mostly mediated by the inducible expression of Fas ligand ( FasL ) as a primary event",
            "relation": "SAME-UNIT"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "leading to the commitment to death . <S>",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT"
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "To gain a better understanding of the transcriptional events",
            "relation": "ENABLEMENT"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "that regulate this expression ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "parent": 0,
            "text": "we took advantage of our previously described mutant Jurkat cells . <S>",
            "relation": "ROOT"
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "These cells are deficient in FasL expression and apoptosis",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "parent": 8,
            "text": "induced upon TCR triggering ,",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT"
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "parent": 8,
            "text": "although their cytokine ( IL-2 and IFN-gamma ) production is normal . <S>",
            "relation": "COMPARISON"
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "Here we show that both a FasL- and a consensus NF-kappaB- reporter construct are inefficiently induced in these cells",
            "relation": "FINDINGS"
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "compared to wild-type cells . <S>",
            "relation": "COMPARISON"
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "In addition , we demonstrate that the inducible transcriptional activity of the FasL reporter is abolished by specific inhibitors of NF-kappaB activation . <S>",
            "relation": "ADDITION"
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "parent": 13,
            "text": "Thus , we could trace the deficit of the mutant cells to an inefficient NF-kappaB activation ,",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT"
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "parent": 14,
            "text": "evidencing a relevant role for NF-kappaB in the regulation of FasL expression in activated T cells . <S>",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT"
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "parent": 13,
            "text": "Furthermore , our results suggest that the induction of FasL versus cytokine gene expression is differentially sensitive to NF-kappaB deprivation . <S>",
            "relation": "ADDITION"
        }
    ]
}